{
  "texts": [
    "For some AI systems, this limitation might not be intrinsic but rather due to the time needed to adapt to new conditions and to learn how to behave in new environments, analogously to what happens with humans.",
    "Still, a consequence of such constraints is that even if omnipresent in our day-to-day lives, the applicability of AI in the real world and its related impact are still limited.",
    "Likewise, AI reliability has further development potential, for both technical and conceptual reasons.",
    "Indeed, some researchers argue for new approaches and paradigm changes in current AI (Marcus and Davis 2019), outlining that one of the main challenges for AI is building learning machines that are as flexible and robust as the biological brain and that have the same capacity for generalization (Sinz et al. 2019).",
    "Moreover, in contrast to AI, which at present can interact with a limited subset of variables within a contextualized environment, biological systems respond to a wide variety of stimuli over long periods of time, and their responses alter the environment and subsequent responses, giving rise to a kind of systemic action-reaction cycle (AA.VV., 2012)."
  ]
}